\section{Interpretation of Exercise Boundaries in Discrete Dividend Models}
In this section, we interpret the results from the Least Squares Monte Carlo (LSMC) and trinomial tree methods for pricing convertible bonds with discrete dividend and coupon payments. The model is based on the two-person zero-sum game framework from Sirbu and Shreve (2006) \cite{sirbu2006two}, where the bondholder maximizes the bond value \(B\) through optimal conversion, while the issuer minimizes \(B\) (maximizing equity \(E = V - B\)) via calls. Chen et al. (2013) \cite{chen2010non} extends this to non-zero-sum games with tax benefits and bankruptcy costs, explaining empirical phenomena like early and late calls, but Sirbu-Shreve provides the foundational theorems for our discrete setup.

\subsection{Model Overview and Mathematical Formulation}
Convertible bonds are hybrid instruments combining debt features (coupons and principal repayment) with equity options (conversion to stock). The issuer may call the bond, forcing conversion or redemption at call price \(K\). In Sirbu-Shreve's model, the firm value \(X_t\) follows a geometric Brownian motion under the risk-neutral measure:
\[
dX_t = r X_t \, dt - c \, dt - \delta S_t \, dt + \sigma X_t \, dW_t,
\]
where \(S_t = X_t - B(t, X_t)\) is equity value, \(c\) is coupon rate, \(\delta\) is dividend rate, \(r\) is risk-free rate, and \(\sigma\) is volatility. Discrete dividends introduce jumps: stock price drops by fraction \(\delta\) at ex-dividend dates, prompting pre-dividend conversion to capture the payout.

The bond value \(B(t, x)\) solves a Dynkin game:
\[
B(s, x) = \sup_{\tau} \inf_{\rho} J(s, x; \rho, \tau),
\]
where \(J\) is the expected discounted cash flows under strategies \(\tau\) (conversion) and \(\rho\) (call). Under conditions \(c \leq rK\) (conversion precedes call) or \(\delta K \leq c\) (call precedes conversion), the game reduces to optimal stopping (Theorem 3.1 in \cite{sirbu2006two}).

In discrete setups, LSMC simulates paths with dividend jumps, regressing continuation values to find exercise boundaries. The trinomial tree discretizes time/space, adjusting for jumps at dividend times.

Financially, discrete dividends create incentives for early conversion: bondholders convert pre-dividend to receive \(\gamma \delta S\), avoiding the stock drop, amplifying the tax-debt trade-off in Chen's model where high tax shields delay calls (late calls) and bankruptcy costs prompt early calls to reduce leverage.

