These prices arise from the Nash equilibrium of the game (Sirbu-Shreve Theorem 4.1), reducing to optimal stopping under certain conditions. The bond value \(B\) satisfies the PDE in continuation regions:
\[
\min\left( \max\left( B - \gamma S, -\mathcal{L}B + c \right), B - K \right) = 0,
\]
where \(\mathcal{L}B = r S \partial_S B + \frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 S^2 \partial_{SS} B - r B\). Discrete dividends modify this to account for jumps, leading to point-like boundaries.

Additionally, varying dividend yields impacts pricing and boundaries, as shown in Table \ref{tab:div_yields}. Higher yields reduce bond prices due to increased dilution but raise early exercise premiums. Financially, higher \(\delta\) increases the incentive to convert pre-dividend, as bondholders miss dividends unless converted, linking to Chen's bankruptcy cost effects where high dividends amplify dilution fears, prompting early calls.

