\subsection{Exercise Boundaries and Discrete Dividends}
The exercise boundaries, plotted in Figure \ref{fig:boundaries}, reveal key insights. The LSMC boundary appears as discrete points, while the tree boundary is sparse or disappears near dividend times (e.g., \(t=1.0\) for single dividend, \(t=0.5,1.0\) for semi-annual).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{exercise_boundaries_full.png} % Replace with your full boundaries plot file
\caption{Exercise boundaries: LSMC (blue points) vs. Tree (orange line). Dashed: Strike \(K=50\). Red dot: Initial stock price \(S_0=50\). Green lines: Dividend times.}
\label{fig:boundaries}
\end{figure}

This sparsity is expected in models with discrete dividends. In continuous models without discrete payouts, the boundary is a smooth curve governed by the Black-Scholes-like PDE (Sirbu-Shreve Equation 2.1):
\[
\min\left( \max\left( B - \gamma S, -\mathcal{L}B + c \right), B - K \right) = 0,
\]
where \(\mathcal{L}B = r S \partial_S B + \frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 S^2 \partial_{SS} B - r B\), \(\gamma\) is the conversion ratio, \(c\) the coupon rate, and \(K\) the call price. The regions are: continuation (hold for coupons), conversion (\(B = \gamma S\)), and call (\(B = K\)).

Sirbu-Shreve Theorem 3.1 states that if \(c < r K\), conversion precedes call (bondholder acts first); if \(\delta K < c\) (\(\delta\): dividend rate), call precedes conversion. In our discrete case, dividends introduce jumps: stock \(S\) drops by \(\delta\) at ex-dividend dates, but bondholders receive no dividend unless converted pre-dividend.

Optimal conversion occurs \textit{right before} dividends to capture the payout:
\[
B(t^-, S) = \max\left( \gamma S (1 + \delta) - \text{lost coupons}, \, e^{-r \Delta t} \mathbb{E}[B(t^+, S(1 - \delta))] + c \Delta t \right).
\]
If \(\gamma \delta S >\) coupon value, convert at \(t^-\), creating point-like boundaries at dividend times. Between dividends, holding may dominate if coupons exceed expected dividends.

In the tree, nodes align with time steps, making the boundary undefined between jumps—hence the ``disappearance'' (sparse points). LSMC regressions naturally yield points from simulated paths. Zoomed plots (Figure \ref{fig:zoom}) confirm clusters at these instants, matching empirical ``early conversions'' before dividends to avoid dilution (cf. Chen et al. for late/early calls). For single dividend, tree zoom shows a downward slope from ~65.5 to 65 near \(t=1\).

Financially, pre-dividend conversion prevents loss from stock drop, as bondholders miss dividends post-drop. This amplifies the game: issuers may call pre-dividend to force surrender (early call per Chen, to reduce bankruptcy risk), or delay for tax shields (late call).

