This discrete behavior explains why continuous approximations (e.g., in Chen) may miss jumps but capture tax/credit effects empirically. In Chen's non-zero-sum extension, tax benefits (\(\kappa\)) delay calls to retain shields, while bankruptcy costs (\(\rho\)) prompt early calls, matching observed returns: positive for out-of-money (good news signal), negative for in-money (dilution).

